properties.title: Acuff Lane
properties.description: Named for Phil and John Acuff, residential developers in Lenexa and Shawnee.

properties.title: Albervan
properties.description: Named after Albert VanLerberg, owner of Van's Food Center in Shawnee.

properties.title: Alden Road
properties.description: Named for William Alden, who donated land for the Greenwood School.

properties.title: Allman Road
properties.description: Named for Robert and Frances Allman, landowners of an area north of 79th and west of Lackman Road.

properties.title: Antioch
properties.description: Originally named Chase Road, it was later renamed Antioch because the Antioch Church was located there.

properties.title: Ballentine
properties.description: Named for John Ballentine, grocer from Kansas City, Kansas who moved to Johnson County in 1919.

properties.title: Barkley Road
properties.description: John Barkley helped develop the area as a member of the Mission Urban Township board.

properties.title: Barton
properties.description: John Barton was the treasurer of Johnson County in 1857 and founder of Olathe.

properties.title: Blackbob Road
properties.description: Blackbob was the recognized chief of the Black Bob Band of Shawnee Indians in the Stanley  Stillwell area

properties.title: Bluejacket Street
properties.description: Named for Charles Bluejacket, a Shawnee Indian who came to Kansas around 1832 and became a highly respected Methodist minister.

properties.title: Bradshaw Drive
properties.description: Named for Charles Bradshaw, one of Lenexa's founders. He and his wife Sarah owned 160 acres at the northwest corner of 95th Street and Noland Road. Lenexa's original town site was carved from their property.

properties.title: Caenen Lake Road
properties.description: Named for Remi Caenen, a farmer, stockman and home developer who came from Belgium as a baby. He built the imposing Caenen Castle at Johnson Drive and Caenen Street in Shawnee.

properties.title: Cedar Creek Road
properties.description: Named after Cedar Creek, a small stream located about 1.5 miles east of De Soto.

properties.title: Cherry Lane
properties.description: Believed to have been named after the Cherry Lane School located at 95th and Woodland.

properties.title: Cody
properties.description: Possibly named after Buffalo Bill Cody

properties.title: College
properties.description: Name changed from 111th street after the construction of Johnson County Community College.

properties.title: Conser
properties.description: John Conser was a pioneer farmer and a prize winning honey raiser in the area. Grant, Johns son, bought several lots at the first auction for the new Overland Park plats and proceeded to build several businesses.

properties.title: Gillette Street
properties.description: Named after H.D. Gillette, who started Lenexa's first blacksmith shop. He came to Lenexa one year after its 1869 platting.

properties.title: Lackman Road
properties.description: Named after William Lackman, who built the Victorian house that the Lenexa Chamber of Commerce now occupies.

properties.title: Lingle Lane
properties.description: Named after Johnna Lingle, Lenexa's first female mayor and a former Johnson County commissioner.

properties.title: Reeder Street
properties.description: Named after the first territorial governor of Kansas, Andrew Horatio Reeder.

properties.title: Renner Boulevard
properties.description: Named for Adam and Anna Renner, farmers who arrived in Johnson County in 1850.
